[codex] RESPONSE: Thank you for providing such clear guidance regarding the next round of review. We have carefully addressed each of the points you raise here. Detailed responses appear in the point-by-point replies to reviewers below, but to summarize:
[codex] We have updated the references Reviewer 1 flagged as dated. Our introduction now provides more contemporary citations (e.g., to Locke and Latham (2019), Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018), Andor, Gerster, and Peters (2020), Henry, Ferraro, and Kontoleon (2019), and Mertens and Schultz (2021)); the General Discussion does the same, incorporating more recent work alongside the foundational citations we retain (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Schultz et al., 2007)
[codex] Relatedly, we have expanded the introductionΓÇÖs theoretical framing (pp. X-X) to articulate why descriptive feedback alone is sufficient to change selection decisions pertaining to women and underrepresented minorities. Consistent with the broader logic of the feedback literature, feedback regulates behavior only when there is a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. However, we now make clear that descriptive feedback can also be effective without a paired goal in domains where a strong implicit standard is already entrenched. This is the case for the types of diversity-related selection decisions we study in our paper, where injunctive norms against prejudicial behavior are sustained by both internal egalitarian commitments and external legal, organizational, and social pressures.
[codex] We have revised the Introduction (pp. X) and Discussion to acknowledge the shifting socio-political landscape around organizational commitments to DEI in the United States flagged by Reviewer 2. We situate our work within two parallel developments. In the U.S., explicit DEI rhetoric has retreated since 2024. In addition, international governments have moved in the opposite direction, passing laws that require firms to disclose or correct gender disparities in pay and leadership. Australia's Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act of 2023 mandates public disclosure of firm-level gender representation and pay gaps (Ressia, 2024). The EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires transposition across member states by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024). The EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% gender minimum on listed-company boards. We argue that these shifts reinforce the contemporary value of our research even against an ever-changing sociopolitical backdrop, with a recent decline in support for corporate diversity policies specifically in the United States.
[codex] We have provided a more tightly bounded theoretical discussion of the scope of our intervention, in line with Reviewer 2ΓÇÖs request. We agree that motivation to respond without prejudice is central to our account of increasing selections of women and racial minorities. However, we also discuss how the organizational climate around DEI is merely one part of the external motivation to control prejudice pathway that can influence individuals when it comes to promoting women and racial minorities. Specifically, the external motivation to control prejudice pathway also encompasses the fact that selection decisions are generally observable by colleagues, prospective candidates, and outside stakeholders, and the implicit norm against appearing prejudiced operates well beyond any one firmΓÇÖs stated commitments. While organizationsΓÇÖ explicit DEI commitments are themselves often responses to external stakeholder, legal, and political pressures rather than the source of internal organizational norms (Levi & Fried, 2024), a given firmΓÇÖs retreat from DEI rhetoric reflects shifting external pressure on the firm, not the disappearance of broader social pressure on individual selection decisions. We also now discuss how the internal motivation to respond without prejudice as well as selectorsΓÇÖ personally-held egalitarian beliefs may not be as malleable in the face of changes in organizational climate, and our existing evidence for why people respond to feedback about the race and gender of their past selectees (see Study 4) is, if anything, more readily explained by internal rather than external motives. In summary, we expect our effect to generalize wherever selections are observable and selectors hold at least some egalitarian commitments, and to be somewhat attenuated in fully private/anonymous selection decisions or in contexts that explicitly encourage discriminatory behavior.
