[codex] RESPONSE: Thank you for this suggestion. We ran the post-test you proposed and incorporated the result into the Discussion of Study 1 (p. X). We recruited N = 300 Prolific participants and randomly assigned each to rate, on a 1 to 7 importance scale, one of the four expert-attribute statements used in Study 1ΓÇÖs feedback manipulation, with the NPR producer framing held constant. Two of the three comparison attributes were rated significantly more important than the gender attribute (ΓÇ£were womenΓÇ¥; M = 3.64, SD = 1.76, n = 76): ΓÇ£worked at a universityΓÇ¥ (M = 4.67, SD = 1.60; t(148.8) = ΓêÆ3.76, p < .001, d = ΓêÆ0.61) and ΓÇ£were under 50 years oldΓÇ¥ (M = 4.44, SD = 1.73; t(149.0) = ΓêÆ2.81, p = .006, d = ΓêÆ0.46). The third, ΓÇ£based on the West Coast of the United States,ΓÇ¥ showed no significant difference in importance (M = 3.37, SD = 1.75; t(149.0) = 0.95, p = .343, d = +0.16). Differences in perceived importance therefore cannot account for why only feedback about gender moved subsequent selections in Study 1, consistent with our claim that descriptive feedback motivates behavior on dimensions carrying an implicit injunctive norm.
[codex] On the request, I liked Study 4b and think that it does a good job of showing that feedback about gender is different than feedback about other important dimensions.  In addition, your studies show that gender/race feedback lead subjects to adjust their portfolios about the base rate.  That said, IΓÇÖm still left wondering whether your findings are showing what you say or it is just that people use these other measures appropriately in their initial selections.  IΓÇÖd like you to at least discuss this possibility, and perhaps there is additional analysis that you can do to address this.
[codex] RESPONSE: Thank you for raising this alternative. We agree it is worth testing directly, and we report a follow-up analysis below (Table R1). We have also added a footnote to the Discussion of Study 4 (p. X) that summarizes this evidence and makes the underlying theoretical claim more explicit in the manuscript.
[codex] In our studies, we make no assumptions about the normative or ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for any attribute in the absence of explicit goals or prescriptions. We expect that a reputational or image concern is activated only after participants receive descriptive feedback, and only for race and gender. This fits the theoretical framing already in the paper: descriptive feedback shifts behavior on a given dimension only when that dimension carries an implicit injunctive norm that the feedback calls into question. We argue this holds for race and gender but not for the comparison attributes we test (see Introduction, p. X, and General Discussion, p. X).
[codex] That said, we can hold the starting point constant by restricting to participants whose initial selections contained zero of the focal attribute. We cannot directly measure what each participant considers an ΓÇ£appropriateΓÇ¥ level for a given attribute, but zero is a reasonable floor and is unlikely to reflect a deliberate level for most participants. In this analysis, we test the hypothesis that feedback motivates selection whenever the initial selections do not reflect appropriate levels. If that were the case, we should see feedback move participants for both race and gender and the comparison attributes in this subset. To test this hypothesis, we pooled participants across Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B with participant-clustered standard errors, restricted to participant observations in which the initial selection contained zero of the focal attribute. We find that race and gender feedback increases the probability of selecting a woman or racial minority by +21.28 percentage points (p < .001, N = 1,222 across all five studies). Whereas, feedback about other attributes increases that probability by only +6.83 percentage points, and is not statistically significant (p = .21, N = 429). A Wald test of the difference between the two pooled coefficients yields +14.46 percentage points (p = .016, 95% CI [+2.70, +26.21]).
[codex] However, we acknowledge that the comparison side of this analysis is meaningfully underpowered, so we can only provide suggestive evidence of our claims. Moreover, we further recognize that zero is a useful but imperfect floor, since for some participants it may reflect a deliberate preference. For these reasons, we treat this analysis as imperfect but directional evidence against the alternative that participants are selecting comparison attributes at appropriate levels to begin with.
