[codex] Study 2
[codex] 
[codex] 	In Study 2, we conducted a framed field experiment (Harrison & List, 2004) to extend our key findings to an in-person, real choice environment in which participants were not aware they were under study. Here we tested whether the key effect of descriptive feedback on selection decisions held when evaluators were making incentive-compatible choices about which prominent figures they would like to feature in a public display in their organization. 
[codex] Methods
[codex] Participants. This study was pre-registered on AsPredicted (https://aspredicted.org/WYY_3PL). We recruited 302 participants to complete a 1-minute survey in exchange for a candy bar (52.52% men; 44.96% women; Mage = 25.11, 41.37% White, 10.79% Black, 4.68% Hispanic, 42.81% Asian) in a high-traffic pedestrian area at a midsize university in the Northeastern United States between March 27 and May 15, 2024. The IRB approved a waiver of informed consent, so participants were not told that they were participating in a research study.
[codex] Procedure. Student recruiters in school-branded clothing (truthfully) told passersby they were conducting a quick vote on which biographies should be displayed at the business school to encourage non-fiction reading; seven books with obscured covers on a table served as a visual prop (see Figure S1 in the Appendix). Participants who agreed were handed an iPad showing 25 well-known biographies, each with a cover thumbnail and a brief description (protagonistΓÇÖs name, role, publication year, page count); five (20%) featured women protagonists.
[codex] Participants were instructed to vote for an initial portfolio of six biographies they would recommend for the on-campus display. After making their initial selections, participants were randomly assigned to either (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants were presented with three pieces of descriptive feedback about their initial six book selections, specifically the percentage of biographies they had selected that (1) were over 500 pages, (2) were written in the past 25 years, and (3) featured an entertainer. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of biographies they had selected featuring a woman protagonist alongside two additional pieces of descriptive feedback that were randomly drawn from the list of three descriptive facts provided in the no gender feedback condition. After receiving descriptive feedback about the composition of their initial selected portfolio of six biographies, participants were asked to vote for a seventh and final biography from the original setΓÇôwhere their prior selections were highlightedΓÇôto include in the display.
[codex] ------------------------------------
[codex] Insert Table 3 about here
[codex] ------------------------------------
[codex] Results 
[codex] Initial selections featured women protagonists 25.2% of the time, with a slight imbalance across conditions (23.0% control vs. 27.3% treatment, p = .050). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors to predict whether the seventh and final biography participants selected featured a woman. Participants were significantly more likely to choose a biography featuring a woman as their seventh and final selection in the gender feedback condition (35.10% did so) than in the no gender feedback condition (21.85% chose a woman; B = 0.132, 95% CI = [0.031, 0.234],┬át(302) = 2.56,┬áp┬á= .011, see Figure 3; Table 3, Model 1).
[codex] As was the case in Study 1, we found no significant effects of the impact of random assignment to receive descriptive feedback about another given biography attribute in a participantΓÇÖs initial portfolio of choices on subsequent selections of biographies with that same attribute (all pΓÇÖs ΓëÑ .5; see Table 3 Models 2-4). 
[codex] Discussion
[codex] 	Study 2 extends our findings in two important ways. First, we find that the effect persists in a field setting where participants made consequential choices. Second, unlike Study 1, here  participants received feedback about their own prior selections rather than hypothetical decisionsΓÇöconfirming that the effect arises even when people reflect on their own past choices. In the next study, we test whether providing feedback about the racial composition of past selectees increases future selections of racial minorities in an incentivized experiment. 
[codex] Study 3
[codex] 
[codex] In Studies 3A and 3B, participants again made a real decision (akin to Study 2) and selected a set of films about famous figures from history to include in a real Facebook advertising campaign. 
[codex] Study 3A
[codex] 
[codex] In Study 3A, we moved beyond testing the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender of prior selectees to testing the effect of descriptive feedback about the race of initial selectees on subsequent selections. 
[codex] 
[codex] Methods
[codex] Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/4z8hk), we recruited 1,000 participants on AmazonΓÇÖs Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (46.1% men; 51.4% women; Mage = 42.20; 72.3% White, 12.0% Black, 6.2% Hispanic, 8.8% Asian).
[codex] Procedure. Participants were truthfully informed about a real Facebook campaign to advertise popular and inspirational biographical films (ΓÇ£biopicsΓÇ¥) and asked to weigh in on which films to include. Participants saw25 candidate films each with a cover art thumbnail and a brief description listing the  protagonistΓÇÖs name (e.g., Judy Garland, Alan Turing), claim to fame (e.g., Actress, WWII codebreaker), the filmΓÇÖs year of release (e.g., 2019, 2014), and budget (e.g., $10m, $14m); 4 of the25 films (16%) featured a racial minority protagonist. 
[codex] Participants selected a portfolio of seven films for the Facebook campaign and  were incentivized for the quality of their decisions. Specifically, we (truthfully) told participants: ΓÇ£To provide extra motivation to take this seriously, weΓÇÖll send you a $5 bonus if your list is selected (there will be an eventual vote on all of the lists generated).ΓÇ¥ 
[codex] Participants were then randomly assigned to either (1) the no race feedback or (2) the race feedback condition. In the no race feedback condition, participants received descriptive feedback on the percentage of films that (1) had a budget above $40M, (2) were released after 2010, and (3) were over 2 hours long. In the race feedback condition, participants always received descriptive feedback about the percentage of films they had selected that featured a racial minority protagonist alongside two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list of film attributes summarized in the no race feedback condition. After receiving descriptive feedback on their initial film selections, participants selected an eighth and final film for the Facebook campaign from the original set, where their prior selections were highlighted. See Materials Section: Study 3A in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] Results
[codex] ParticipantsΓÇÖ initial selections featured racial minority protagonists 16.1% of the time, with balance across conditions (p┬á= .314, see Appendix Table S3). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors to predict whether the eighth and final biopic selected featured a racial minority protagonist, using assignment to the race feedback condition as the primary predictor Participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist in the race feedback condition (27.10% chose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist) than in the no race feedback condition (17.73% chose a biopic featuring a racial minority protagonist;┬áB┬á= 0.094, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.145],┬át(998) = 3.57,┬áp┬á< .001).The effect of assignment to the race feedback condition on the subsequent selection of a racial minority protagonist was significantly larger than the effects of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about any of the three comparison attributes (all pΓÇÖs Γëñ .009; see Table S3, Models 5-8 for the per-study system-of-equations results). 
[codex] Study 3B
[codex] In this study, we sought to replicate our key findings from Study 3A about how feedback affects real selection decisions, but this time we provide descriptive feedback about the gender distribution of past selectees. 
[codex] Methods
[codex] Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/uyn8g/), we recruited 1,000 participants on Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (51.0% men; 48.3% women; Mage = 43.60; 77.9% White, 9.7% Black, 5.5% Hispanic, 6.4% Asian).
[codex] Procedure. The procedure in this study was nearly identical to the procedure described in Study 3A, but we changed the selection set of biopics to include 19 films featuring male protagonists and 6 featuring female protagonists (so 24% of the protagonists were women). Participants also began by selecting an initial portfolio of six films for inclusion in the Facebook advertising campaign instead of seven. The brief description provided of each film did not state the length of the film; instead, it presented information about the film protagonistΓÇÖs profession (e.g., ΓÇ£A film about George W. Bush. Who was he? 43rd U.S. President.ΓÇ¥). 
[codex] Just as in the prior study, after making their set of six initial film selections, participants were randomly assigned to either (1) the no gender feedback condition or (2) the gender feedback condition. In the no gender feedback condition, participants were presented with feedback about the percentage of films they had selected that (1) had a budget above $40M, (2) were released after 2010, and (3) included a political leader as the protagonist. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of films they had selected featuring a woman protagonist, in addition to two more pieces of descriptive feedback randomly selected from the three in the no gender feedback condition. Otherwise, the study was identical to Study 3A. See Materials Section: Study 3B in the Appendix for complete study materials.
[codex] Results
[codex] On average, 17.5% of participantsΓÇÖ initially selected films featured female protagonists, with balance across conditions (p = 0.813; see Appendix Table/Section X). As shown in Figure S2B and in our primary, pre-registered OLS regression (Model 1 of Table S5), participants were significantly more likely to choose a biopic featuring a woman protagonist as their seventh and final film in the gender feedback condition (40.64% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist) than in the no gender feedback condition (20.08% chose a biopic with a woman protagonist; B = 0.206, 95% CI = [0.150, 0.261], t(998) = 7.24, p < .001, see Table S5 Model 1). These results were robust to several alternative specifications, including controlling for participant gender, race, and age, and analyzing our data with logistic regression (see Appendix Table S6 for robustness checks). In addition, as shown in Figure S2B and Table S5 (Models 5-8), and as predicted, the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a 7th film with a woman protagonist was larger than the effect of assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the percentage of initial films selected with a (1) budget above $40M (F(1, 1992) = 65.06, p < .001), (2) political leader protagonist (F(1, 1992) = 57.74, p < .001), or (3) release year after 2010 (F(1, 1992) = 12.44, p < .001) on subsequent selections of a 7th and final biopic with, respectively, a (1) budget above $40M, (2) political leader protagonist, or (3) release year after 2010 (in fact, all other types of feedback had insignificant effects on subsequent film selections).
[codex] Discussion
[codex] Across two incentivized experiments,  descriptive feedback about the race (Study 3A) or gender (Study 3B) of protagonists featured in previously selected films increased subsequent selections of films featuring racial minorities or women, respectively. One possible explanation for our findings is that the feedback itself signaled that we value racial or gender diversity: after initially choosing films based on personal preferences, participants may have inferred from race or gender feedback that these attributes mattered to the experimenter and attended to these attributes more in subsequent decisions as a result of a ΓÇ£demand effectΓÇ¥ (Orne, 1962; Zizzo, 2010). If this alternative explanation were driving our effects, however, we would also expect participants to respond to the ΓÇ£demand effectΓÇ¥ inherent in receiving feedback about other attributes of their selected films (e.g., feedback about a filmΓÇÖs budget or year of release), but we found no such patterns. 
[codex] However, to further rule out a ΓÇ£demand effectΓÇ¥ explanation for our findings, we conducted two supplemental experiments (Studies S2A and S2B, detailed in pages 7-11 in the Appendix). In both studies, we employed a 2x2 design that crossed our original gender feedback manipulation with the addition of a values-based injunctive message (i.e., ΓÇ£The organization planning this event cares deeply about presenting a diversity of speakers in terms of [their experience in CEO roles, their experience as company founders, their background in the technology industry] and their gender.ΓÇ¥) to the participant emphasizing the importance of making diverse selections. Study S2A involved hypothetical selections of corporate speakers to join a high-profile panel;Study S2B involved incentivized selections of podcasts to feature in a Facebook ad campaign. In both studies, we replicated our finding from Study 3B: descriptive feedback about the gender of past selectees increased the likelihood that participants subsequently selected a woman. However, explicitly highlighting the importance of making diverse selections (via an explicit injunctive norm message) did not significantly increase the selection of women candidates (in S2A: the message produced a regression-estimated 3% increase in the selection of women panelists,┬áB┬á= 0.030,┬áp┬á= .471; in S2B: the message produced a regression-estimated 5% increase in the selection of podcasts with women hosts,┬áB┬á= 0.053,┬áp┬á= .176). Moreover, in neither study did the effect of the explicit injunctive norm message highlighting the importance of diverse selections significantly alter the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender of past selectees (Study S2A interaction:┬áB┬á= -0.005,┬áp┬á= .941; Study S2B interaction:┬áB┬á= 0.019,┬áp┬á= .748; see Appendix Tables S17-S22 for full results). Together, these findings suggest our results in Study 3 are not the product of an experimenter demand effect. 
[codex] Study 4
[codex] 
[codex] In Study 4, we tested the mechanism we theorize underlies the relationship between descriptive feedback and subsequent selection decisions: motivation to respond without prejudice. 
[codex] We also attempted to rule out the possibility that the ΓÇ£comparisonΓÇ¥ attributes summarized in descriptive feedback (alongside feedback about the race or gender of past selectees) in our prior studies may have been perceived as less important to participants than the race and gender of candidates. In Study 4B, we selected comparison attributes after pre-testing them for importance, and we ensured that all were rated at least as important as gender or race. See Appendix Study S4 for a complete description of our pre-testing procedure and results.
[codex] We examined the effect of feedback about the race of past selectees in Study 4A and feedback about the gender of past selectees in Study 4B. 
[codex] Study 4A
[codex] 
[codex] Methods
[codex] Participants. As pre-registered (https://aspredicted.org/XGG_21R), we recruited 1,000 participants on AmazonΓÇÖs Cloudresearch to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (47.6% men, 51.5% women; Mage = 42.53; 75.75% White, 9.21% Black, 4.75% Hispanic, 8.83% Asian). 
[codex] Procedure. Participants imagined being  tasked with creating a reading list for their local library. They were presented with a 25 (real) authors, each shown with a small photograph and a brief description listing the authorΓÇÖs name (e.g., James Baldwin, Isabel Allende), most notable work (e.g., Go Tell It on the Mountain, The House of the Spirits), and a count of their total published works (e.g., ΓÇ£authored 6 books and several short stories and poemsΓÇ¥; ΓÇ£authored 6 booksΓÇ¥). Eight of the 25 authors (32%) were racial minorities.
[codex] Participants selected an initial portfolio of six authors and were randomly assigned to one of two conditions: (1) the no race feedback condition or (2) the race feedback condition. In the no race feedback condition, participants received summary statistics about the percentage of selected authors who (1) were born in the 1800s, (2) wrote more than 10 books, and/or (3) wrote poetry. In the race feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of authors they had selected who were racial minorities, alongside one or two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list above.
[codex] After receiving feedback, participants selected a seventh and final author to recommend for their local libraryΓÇÖs summer fiction reading list from the original author candidate set, where their prior selections were highlighted. Finally, participants were asked questions to assess their internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice. See Materials Section: Study 4A for full study materials. 
[codex] Internal motivation to respond without prejudice. To assess internal motives (e.g., image concerns) in the final author selection, we adapted four items from Plant and DevineΓÇÖs (1998) internal motivation to respond without prejudice scale (e.g., ΓÇ£Given my personal values and beliefs, an important factor in my selection of the seventh author to add to my list was my desire to promote the success of racial minorities.ΓÇ¥; CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.93). Items used a  1 (Strongly disagree) to 7 (Strongly agree) scale and, as pre-registered, were separately z-scored and then averaged.
[codex] External motivation to respond without prejudice. To assess external motives (e.g., reputational concerns) in the final author selection,  we adapted three items from Plant and DevineΓÇÖs external motivation to respond without prejudice scale (e.g., ΓÇ£When making my decision about who to select as my seventh author, I considered the social pressures I face to appear to promote racial minorities where they are typically underrepresented.ΓÇ¥; CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.90). Items used a 1 (Strongly disagree) to 7 (Strongly agree) scale, and as pre-registered, were separately z-scored and then averaged. 
[codex] Results
[codex] Initial selections featured racial minority authors 21.8% of the time, with balance across conditions (p┬á= .114; see Appendix Table S7). Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regression with robust standard errors predicting whether the seventh and final author a participant selected was a racial minority, with assignment to the race feedback condition as the primary predictor. We again replicated the findings from our previous studies (see Table S7 for complete results): Participants were significantly more likely to choose a racial minority author in the race feedback condition (41.60% chose a racial minority author) than in the no race feedback condition (28.20% chose a racial minority author;┬áB┬á= 0.134, 95% CI = [0.075, 0.193],┬át(998) = 4.48,┬áp┬á< .001; see Table S7, Model 1). In addition, as predicted, we again found that the effect of providing feedback about the race of initial selectees is significantly larger than the effects of providing descriptive feedback about other attributes of initial selectees (poets:┬áF(1, 3984) = 6.19,┬áp┬á= .013; wrote > 10 books:┬áF(1, 3984) = 5.50,┬áp┬á= .019; born in 1800s:┬áF(1, 3984) = 5.26,┬áp┬á= .022; see Table S7, Models 5-8).
[codex] Mediation. Following our pre-registration, we tested each proposed mediator independently using a 10,000-sample bootstrapped mediation model and a Sobel test. The 95% bias-corrected CI for the size of the indirect effect of internal motivation to respond without prejudice excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.06, 95% CI = [0.034, 0.09], suggesting that internal motivation to respond without prejudice helped account for the effect of assignment to the race feedback condition on selecting a racial minority as the final author. Using Imai et al.ΓÇÖs (2010) average causal mediation effect approach, 44.7% of the effect occurred through mediation by the participantΓÇÖs internal motivation to respond without prejudice. In addition, the 95% bias-corrected CI for the size of the indirect effect of external motivation to respond without prejudice excludes zero (indirect effect = 0.019, 95% CI = [0.005, 0.03]), suggesting that participantsΓÇÖ external motivation to respond without prejudice also helped account for the effect of assignment to the race feedback condition (vs. no race feedback) on selecting a racial minority final author. The average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 14.1% of the effect occurred through external motivation to respond without prejudice. 
[codex] We next tested for both mediators in a multiple mediation model (as preregistered), which addressed address potential multicollinearity between these correlated measures (rΓÇë=ΓÇë0.72, p < 0.001). Once accounting for the correlation between constructs, internal motivation to respond without prejudice (indirect effect = 0.08, 95% CI = [0.042, 0.11]), significantly mediated the effect  whereas external motivation to respond without prejudice (indirect effect = -0.014, 95% CI = [-0.03, 0.00]) did not.  
[codex] Study 4B
[codex] In this study, we replicate our key findings from Study 4A, but this time we provide feedback about the gender (rather than race) of the initial selectees. Prior to this study, we conducted a pretest (N = 550) rating 21 candidate author attributes on importance for selecting authors (see Appendix Section S4 for full details); allowing us to select three comparison attributes that did not differ significantly from gender on rated importance.
[codex] Given that liberals and conservatives differ not only in their attitudes toward diversity but also in their understanding of what diversity means (Howard, Cervone, & Motyl, 2022), and that recent research suggests diversity initiatives may produce divergent reactions across the political spectrum (Hachem & Dover, 2024), we also examine whether participantsΓÇÖ political ideology moderates the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender of past selectees.
[codex] Methods
[codex] 	Participants. As pre-registered (https://osf.io/de3bu/), we recruited 1,000 participants through Prolific Academic to complete a 3-minute survey for $0.75 (48.0% men, 50.7% women, 1.1% non-binary; Mage = 43.0; 75.9% White, 10.8% Black, 4.8% Hispanic, 8.0% Asian).
[codex] Procedure. As in Study 4A, a list of 25 (real) authors was presented to each participant to consider for inclusion in a reading list for their local library. Each author was displayed with a photograph, the authorΓÇÖs name (e.g., Kurt Vonnegut), most notable work (e.g., Slaughterhouse-Five), an estimate of their most notable workΓÇÖs all-time sales and time in print (e.g., 800K copies sold, in print 56 years), their number of works authored (e.g., 14 books, 3 essays), and their genre(s) (e.g., Science Fiction, Satire). Six of the authors on this list (24%) were women.
[codex] Following a similar procedure to the one described in Study 4A, participants were randomly assigned to one of two conditions: participants in the no gender feedback condition received summary statistics about the percentage of authors they had selected who (1) wrote works spanning multiple genres, (2) had at least one book with 30 million or more copies sold, and/or (3) had works that remained in continuous print for over 50 years. In the gender feedback condition, participants always received feedback about the percentage of authors they had selected who were women, alongside two randomly drawn pieces of feedback from the list of items in the no gender feedback condition. After receiving feedback, participants selected a seventh and final author to recommend for their local libraryΓÇÖs winter fiction reading list from the original candidate set, where their prior selections were highlighted. 
[codex] After making all decisions, participants were asked questions to assess their internal (CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.93) and external (CronbachΓÇÖs ╬▒ = 0.89) motivation to respond without prejudice, which were identical to the questions in Study 4A except for word changes made to focus on avoiding gender prejudice rather than racial prejudice. See Materials Section: Study 4B for full study materials. 
[codex] Political ideology. To measure participantsΓÇÖ political orientation, we used the 7-point political ideology scale from the American National Election Studies (ANES, 2022). Participants responded to the prompt ΓÇ£When it comes to politics, do you usually think of yourself as...?ΓÇ¥ on a scale ranging from 1 (Extremely liberal) to 7 (Extremely conservative), with 4 representing Moderate; middle of the road. This measure was centered at 4 (moderate) for analyses examining moderation effects.
[codex] Political party affiliation. To assess participantsΓÇÖ political party identification, we adapted the party identification item from the American National Election Studies (ANES, 2022). Participants were asked ΓÇ£Generally speaking, do you usually think of yourself as a Republican, a Democrat, or an Independent?ΓÇ¥ and selected one of three options: Democrat, Republican, or Independent. For regression analyses, party affiliation was dummy coded with Republican as the reference category.
[codex] Results 
[codex] Initial selections featured women authors 25.3% of the time, with balance across conditions (p = .679; see Appendix Table S9).
[codex] Following our pre-registration, we ran an OLS regressions with robust standard errors predicting whether the seventh and final author a participant selected was a woman, with assignment to the gender feedback condition as the primary predictor First, we replicated the primary findings from our previous studies (see Table S9 for complete regression results): participants were significantly more likely to choose a woman author as their final selectee in the gender feedback condition (41.48% chose a woman author) than in the no gender feedback condition (29.54% chose a woman author; B = 0.119, 95% CI = [0.060, 0.178], t(998) = 3.97, p < .001; Table S9, Model 1).
[codex] In addition, as theorized, we found that the effect of providing descriptive feedback about the gender of initial selectees is significantly larger than the effect of providing descriptive feedback about whether participantsΓÇÖ initial selectees wrote works spanning multiple genres (F(1, 1992) = 37.92, p < .001), wrote at least one book with 30 million or more copies sold (F(1, 1992) = 11.48, p < .001), or wrote any works that remained in continuous print for over 50 years (F(1, 1992) = 9.01, p = .003; see Table S9, Models 5-8).
[codex] Mediation. Following our pre-registration, we tested each proposed mediator independently using a 10,000-sample bootstrapped mediation model and a Sobel test (Imai et al., 2010). The 95% bias-corrected CI for the indirect effect of internal motivation to respond without prejudice excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.064, 95% CI = [0.037, 0.094]), suggesting that internal motivation partially accounted for the effect of assignment to the gender feedback condition on the likelihood of selecting a woman as the final author; the average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 53.9% of the effect occurred through internal motivation. Next, the 95% bias-corrected CI for the indirect effect of external motivation excluded zero (indirect effect = 0.030, 95% CI = [0.014, 0.048]), suggesting that external motivation likewise accounted for the effect; the average causal mediation effect approach suggested that 24.8% of the effect occurred through external motivation. 
[codex] We next tested both mediators in a multiple mediation model (these items were highly correlated: r = 0.78, p < .001). The results confirmed that internal motivation to respond without prejudice (indirect effect = 0.091, 95% CI = [0.052, 0.131]) significantly mediated the effect. When both mediators were included simultaneously, external motivation to respond without prejudice showed a significant negative indirect effect (indirect effect = -0.028, 95% CI = [-0.046, -0.012]).
[codex] To test whether political ideology or party affiliation moderated our effects, we added pre-registered interaction terms to our primary model. We found no significant interaction between assignment to the gender feedback condition and political ideology (B = -0.013, 95% CI = [-0.044, 0.018], t(996) = -0.80, p = .424), nor did we find significant interactions between assignment to the gender feedback condition and party affiliation (Democrat interaction: B = 0.019, 95% CI = [-0.125, 0.164], t(994) = 0.26, p = .792; Independent interaction: B = 0.067, 95% CI = [-0.085, 0.220], t(994) = 0.87, p = .387), 
[codex] Discussion
[codex] In Study 4, we again replicated the effect of descriptive feedback about the race and gender of past selectees increasing the subsequent selection of racial minorities and women. In addition, we found evidence that both internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice mediated this effect for subsequent selections of racial minorities (Study 4A) and women (Study 4B), respectively. When combining the highly correlated measures of internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice in a multiple mediation model, our findings suggest that internal motivation is the dominant mediator in our studies. However, external motivation to respond without prejudice could likely play a more significant role in settings where choices are made publicly. 
[codex] In addition, Study 4B established that the effect of gender feedback was not moderated by political ideology nor party affiliation. Finally, it ruled out the possibility that our effects were driven by perceptions of which attributes were considered most important.
[codex] Study 5
[codex] In all of our studies so far, we examined situations where women or racial minorities were underrepresented in candidate pools, which means that mechanically they would also likely be underrepresented in many respondentsΓÇÖ initial set of selectees. As a result, the descriptive feedback we delivered typically highlighted that historically underrepresented groups had been picked at low rates (in fact, across all studies thus far, 83% of participants who received feedback about the gender or race of past selectees learned that the candidates they had initially selected were less than half women or racial minorities, respectively). In Study 5, we tested how descriptive feedback affects decision makers when it suggests that historically underrepresented groups have recently been picked at high rates. This would not, in theory, activate a motivation to respond without prejudice, since the initial feedback would indicate that historically underrepresented groups were being well-represented. Under such circumstances, we would no longer predict a positive effect of descriptive feedback about past decisions on the subsequent selection of candidates from a historically underrepresented population.
[codex] Before testing this prediction experimentally, we examined whether the size of the effect we study differs based on the proportion of women and racial minorities initially selected by re-analyzing data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B. Specifically, we tested for an interaction between (1) the proportion of women or racial minorities a participant initially selected (before random assignment to condition) for inclusion in their portfolio and (2) random assignment to receive descriptive feedback about the fraction of women or racial minorities in their original portfolio of selectees. Based on our theorizing that feedback is unlikely to evoke a motivation to respond without prejudice when initial selections of women or racial minorities are high, we would predict a negative interaction between these predictors.
[codex] ------------------------------------------------------------------
[codex] Insert Table 4 about here 
[codex] ------------------------------------------------------------------ 
[codex] In Table 4, Models 1-5, we present five regression models re-analyzing data from Studies 2, 3A, 3B, 4A, and 4B, in which we added two new predictors: (1) the proportion of racial minorities or women (depending on the study) in the initially selected candidate set and (2) an interaction between this predictor and our primary predictor: assignment to the race feedback or gender feedback condition (depending on the study). In Model 1, which analyzes data from Study 2 (gender), we found the predicted significant negative interaction between the proportion of women selected initially and the impact of assignment to the gender feedback condition on subsequent selections of women (B = -0.107, 95% CI = [-0.198, -0.015], t(298) = -2.30, p = .022). In Model 2, which analyzes data from Study 3A (race), we found only directional but insignificant evidence of the predicted negative interaction between the proportion of racial minorities selected initially and the impact of assignment to the race feedback condition on subsequent selections of racial minorities (B = -0.019, 95% CI = [-0.070, 0.032], t(996) = -0.73, p = .465). In Model 3, which analyzes data from Study 3B (gender), we found the predicted significant negative interaction between the proportion of women selected initially and the impact of assignment to the gender feedback condition on subsequent selections of women (B = -0.087, 95% CI = [-0.141, -0.034], t(996) = -3.20, p = .001). In Model 4, which analyzed data from Study 4A (race), we found marginally significant evidence of the predicted negative interaction (B = -0.044, 95% CI = [-0.088, 0.001], t(996) = -1.92, p = .055). And in Model 5, which analyzed data from Study 4B (gender), we found a significant negative interaction (B = -0.046, 95% CI = [-0.090, -0.002], t(996) = -2.06, p = .040), as predicted. 	To quantify the overall pattern of interactions across these five studies, we conducted a mini meta-analysis combining the interaction coefficients from Models 1-5 (Goh et al., 2016). Specifically, we pooled the five coefficients representing the interaction between assignment to the gender (Study 2, 3B, and 4B) or race (Study 3A and 4A) feedback condition and the proportion of women or racial minorities initially selected. Using a random-effects model, which weighs each studyΓÇÖs contribution by its standard error, we found a significant negative pooled interaction effect (B = -0.052, 95% CI = [-0.075, -0.028], z = -4.36, p < .001). This suggests that the effect of descriptive feedback on female and racial minority selections is reliably larger when participants have selected a lower initial proportion of women or racial minorities and receive feedback to this effect.
[codex] However, because the proportion of women or racial minorities in participantsΓÇÖ initial selections was not randomly assigned (although selections were made before random assignment) and was somewhat restricted in range, we conducted an experiment where we used our standard experimental setup from Studies 2-4 but exogenously varied whether women made up the minority versus the majority of candidates available for selection. We then examined how exogenously manipulating whether people likely select very few versus very many female candidates related to the effect of descriptive feedback about the gender of their past selectees on the gender of their subsequent selectees.
