[codex] 69: Thanks for the opportunity to review this paper, which has improved substantially since the last round. I appreciate the authorsΓÇÖ attentiveness to most of the comments raised previously. After reading this version, I have two comments.
[codex] 70: RESPONSE: Thank you for your kind words about how much you feel our manuscript has improved. We are grateful for your feedback, which we feel has helped us improve the paper immensely.
[codex] 71: First, the paper, as written, feels a bit dated in several spots (e.g., early intro, then pp.4-5, and Discussion) given all that has transpired with respect to pull back on DEI commitments and practices in the US. ItΓÇÖs not clear how many companies are still providing diversity scorecards or numerical feedback about demographic representation, but itΓÇÖs certainly a smaller number than when this research project began, and perhaps, more importantly, the broader tides have shifted. The one sentence on p.5 ΓÇô ΓÇ£and despiteΓÇªΓÇ¥ - is not sufficient and is perhaps misleading. The authors should find a way to acknowledge this through the narrative, and more accurately depict the current state so that the article does not feel timestamped and detached as if it was written in a pre-2024 period. While doing this, they should find a way to reinforce the reasons why their question and intervention remain important.
[codex] 72: RESPONSE: Thank you for this comment. We have updated the Introduction (pp. X) and the Discussion to situate the paper more explicitly in the current socio-political landscape with respect to DEI efforts.
[codex] 73: The revised manuscript now more thoroughly discusses the fluctuating corporate posture toward DEI over the past five years: a period in which many U.S. organizations first rapidly adopted pro-DEI rhetoric and commitments, and then many of those same organizations have since scaled back on those commitments under new political, legal, and reputational pressures. At the same time, we also acknowledge two countervailing patterns that have occurred in parallel. First, internationally, regulatory demand for transparency around demographic representation is expanding: AustraliaΓÇÖs Workplace Gender Equality Amendment (Closing the Gender Pay Gap) Act 2023 mandates public reporting of firm-level gender representation and pay-gap data (Ressia, 2024); the EU Pay Transparency Directive 2023/970 requires member-state transposition by June 2026 (Mignano, 2024); and the EU Women on Boards Directive 2022/2381 establishes a 40% representation objective for the underrepresented gender on listed-company boards. Second, within the U.S., public and investor sentiment has shifted more slowly than corporate rhetoric. A 2025 Bentley/Gallup survey reports that 69% of U.S. adults believe businesses should promote DEI (Bentley/Gallup, 2025), and anti-DEI shareholder proposals have failed at numerous prominent organizations including Costco , Apple, LeviΓÇÖs, John Deere, Goldman Sachs, and others (CBS, 2025; Marketplace, 2025).Together, these patterns help explain why many (though not all) U.S. firms have rebranded their diversity functions rather than dismantled them. For example, Constellation Brands now uses ΓÇ£Inclusive Culture Team,ΓÇ¥ KohlΓÇÖs has shifted to ΓÇ£Chief Inclusion and Belonging Officer,ΓÇ¥ and Nationwide and UPS have migrated to ΓÇ£belonging,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£respect,ΓÇ¥ ΓÇ£fairness,ΓÇ¥ or ΓÇ£inclusive experiencesΓÇ¥ framings (CNBC, 2025; HRGrapevine, 2025; Marketplace, 2026). Paradigm reports a 22% decrease in Fortune 100 references to ΓÇ£DEI/diversityΓÇ¥ between 2023 and 2024 alongside a 59% increase in references to ΓÇ£belongingΓÇ¥ (Paradigm, 2025).In summary, we now situate the research more thoughtfully against the current landscape, acknowledging the shifts that have unfolded while clarifying the contexts in which this work remains both important and necessary.
