[codex]   revision-analysis\_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:167:        	Across seven pre-registered experiments, 
[codex] including a framed field study in a real organization, we investigate the impact of providing descriptive feedback 
[codex] about the gender and racial diversity of past candidate selections on evaluatorsΓÇÖ future choices. In Studies 1-5 we 
[codex] demonstrate that when women (or racial minorities) are underrepresented in candidate pools, giving participants 
[codex] feedback about the fraction of women (or racial minorities) they initially select increases the likelihood that they 
[codex] will subsequently choose to add a woman (or racial minority) to their portfolio. By contrast, when participants 
[codex] receive descriptive feedback about the fraction of selectees with other domain-relevant attributes that are 
[codex] DEI-irrelevant (e.g., the fraction of Technologists on a panel instead of the fraction of women on that panel), it 
[codex] does not have the same impact on their subsequent selections (i.e., they are less likely to subsequently select a 
[codex] Technologist). In Studies 4A and 4B, we identify peopleΓÇÖs motivation to respond without prejudice as a key mechanism 
[codex] underlying the effect of descriptive feedback on peopleΓÇÖs subsequent DEI-related selection decisions. We find that 
[codex] both internal and external motivation to respond without prejudice mediates the relationship between receiving 
[codex] descriptive feedback about past selectees and making more gender-or-racially-diverse future candidate selections. 
[codex]   revision-analysis\_r2_review\manuscript_gdoc_text.txt:168:However, we do find an important moderator of our effect: 
[codex] in settings where feedback highlights that candidates who have historically faced discrimination are overrepresented 
[codex] among selectees, the effect shrinks and reverses, prompting people to strive for parity by adjusting their picks in 
[codex] the opposite direction (see Study 5).
