[codex] > According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback most effectively regulates behavior change when paired with explicit goals, norms or targets that allow recipients to gauge their performance and direct their efforts accordingly (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996, 1998; Locke & Latham, 2019; Itzchakov & Latham, 2018; Chen, Latham, & Piccolo, 2020).
[codex] >
[codex] > Taken together, the original Schultz et al. (2007) findings and later reprise by Schultz, Nolan, and Cialdini (2018) underscore that descriptive feedback is most effective when it is accompanied by normative information about what behavior is desirable, a conclusion echoed in more recent applied feedback interventions in energy and household conservation domains (Andor, Gerster, & Peters, 2020; Henry, Ferraro, & Kontoleon, 2019; Mertens & Schultz, 2021).
[codex] 
[codex] Why this wording: The first sentence preserves the existing manuscript sentence and only updates the citation block. The second sentence makes the classic social-norms example do more theoretical work while adding the applied feedback citations without overstating that feedback alone is effective.
