[codex] ## Draft 2
[codex] 
[codex] Locator: New Introduction paragraph immediately before ΓÇ£We propose that when descriptive feedback reveals that an evaluatorΓÇÖs past selections included few women or racial minorities...ΓÇ¥.
[codex] 
[codex] > This logic implies a boundary condition on when descriptive feedback alone should motivate change. The classical feedback literature establishes that pairing feedback with an explicit goal can work because it supplies a standard against which past performance can be evaluated. However, an explicit goal should be less necessary when a strong implicit standard is already entrenched. Diversity-related selection decisions provide a clean test of this claim because anti-discrimination law, social and reputational pressures to avoid appearing prejudiced, and selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian self-image jointly sustain an entrenched implicit injunctive norm against prejudiced selection (Plant & Devine, 1998; Crandall & Eshleman, 2003; ├ülvarez-Benjumea, 2023). When descriptive feedback reveals a discrepancy between that implicit standard and past behavior, we theorize that motivation to respond without prejudice will be activated even in the absence of a specific external goal.
[codex] 
[codex] Why this wording: This paragraph closely follows the response letterΓÇÖs theoretical promise while making the standard-setting logic explicit. It positions diversity-related selection as the clean test case rather than making a broad claim about all descriptive feedback.
[codex] 
[codex] ## Draft 3
[codex] 
[codex] Locator: General Discussion paragraph beginning ΓÇ£Our work makes two primary theoretical contributions...ΓÇ¥.
[codex] 
[codex] > According to Feedback Intervention Theory, feedback is most effective when paired with explicit goals, standards, or explicit injunctive norms that signal a clear gap between current performance and a desired state (Kluger & DeNisi, 1996; Locke & Latham, 2019; Schultz et al., 2007; Schultz, Nolan, & Cialdini, 2018).
[codex] 
[codex] Why this wording: This is the targeted citation-block replacement requested. It keeps the existing General Discussion claim intact while adding the contemporary goal-setting and social-norms citations.
