[codex] ## Draft 4
[codex] 
[codex] Locator: General Discussion, Theoretical and Practical Contributions section, after the sentence ending ΓÇ£an implicit injunctive norm to avoid prejudice has already been internalized by the decision-maker.ΓÇ¥
[codex] 
[codex] > Our account also clarifies two forms of motivation through which descriptive feedback can change selection decisions. External motivation to control prejudice should be strongest when selection decisions are observable to colleagues, prospective candidates, supervisors, customers, employees, or outside stakeholders, and when evaluators face legal accountability or reputational costs for choices that appear exclusionary. In this sense, firmsΓÇÖ public DEI rhetoric is better understood as one downstream signal of broader legal, employee, customer, and reputational pressures, rather than the source of the implicit injunctive norm itself (Levi & Fried, 2024). Internal motivation to control prejudice, by contrast, reflects selectorsΓÇÖ personally held egalitarian beliefs and their desire to view themselves as non-prejudiced decision makers. This latter mechanism may be less sensitive to a given organizationΓÇÖs current DEI rhetoric, and it is the pathway most directly supported by Study 4, where feedback was delivered privately and internal motivation to respond without prejudice mediated subsequent selections. Study 4BΓÇÖs political-ideology null is consistent with this broader account, suggesting that external motivation to control prejudice and internal motivation to control prejudice may both operate across the political spectrum.
[codex] 
[codex] Why this wording: The paragraph separates external and internal motivation without treating firm rhetoric as the cause of the norm. The final sentence incorporates the requested political-ideology connection while keeping the interpretation conservative.
[codex] 
